# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: use-method
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:use-method/bottleneck-software] In software engineering, a **bottleneck** occurs when the capacity of an application or a computer system is limited by a single component, like the neck of a bottle slowing down the overall water flow.
[src:use-method/bottleneck-software] The bottleneck has the lowest throughput of all parts of the transaction path.
[src:use-method/bottleneck-software] System designers try to avoid bottlenecks through direct effort towards locating and tuning existing bottlenecks in a software application.
[src:use-method/bottleneck-software] Some examples of engineering bottlenecks that appear include the following: a processor, a communication link, and disk IO.
[src:use-method/bottleneck-software] A system or application will hit a bottleneck if the work arrives at a comparatively faster pace relative to other processing components.
[src:use-method/bottleneck-software] According to the theory of constraints, improving on the occurrences of hot-spot point of the bottleneck constraint improves the overall processing speed of the software.
[src:use-method/bottleneck-software] A thought-provoking stipulation of the theory reveals that improving the efficiency of a particular process stage rather than the constraint can generate even more delay and decrease overall processing capabilities of a software.
[src:use-method/bottleneck-software] It is impossible to remove bottlenecks completely since there is always a component that limits the overall performance, so the usual goal is to improve the bottleneck component so that the whole system can achieve the desired performance.
[src:use-method/bottleneck-software] The process of tracking down bottlenecks (also referred as "hot spots" - sections of the code that execute most frequently - i.e. have the highest execution count) is called performance analysis.
[src:use-method/bottleneck-software] Reduction is achieved with the utilization of specialized tools such as performance analyzers or profilers, the objective being to make particular sections of code perform as effectively as possible to improve overall algorithmic efficiency.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] In computing, **computer performance** is the amount of useful work accomplished by a computer system.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Outside specific contexts, computer performance is estimated in terms of accuracy, efficiency and speed of executing computer program instructions.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] The performance of any computer system can be evaluated in measurable, technical terms, using one or more of the metrics listed above.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Computer software performance, particularly software application response time, is an aspect of software quality that is important in human–computer interactions.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Performance engineering continuously deals with trade-offs between types of performance.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Occasionally a CPU designer can find a way to make a CPU with better overall performance by improving one of the aspects of performance, presented below, without sacrificing the CPU's performance in other areas.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] For example, building the CPU out of better, faster transistors.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] However, sometimes pushing one type of performance to an extreme leads to a CPU with worse overall performance, because other important aspects were sacrificed to get one impressive-looking number, for example, the chip's clock rate (see the megahertz myth).
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Application Performance Engineering (APE) is a specific methodology within performance engineering designed to meet the challenges associated with application performance in increasingly distributed mobile, cloud and terrestrial IT environments.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] It includes the roles, skills, activities, practices, tools and deliverables applied at every phase of the application lifecycle that ensure an application will be designed, implemented and operationally supported to meet non-functional performance requirements.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Computer performance metrics (things to measure) include availability, response time, channel capacity, latency, completion time, service time, bandwidth, throughput, relative efficiency, scalability, performance per watt, compression ratio, instruction path length and speed up.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Availability of a system is typically measured as a factor of its reliability.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] As reliability increases, so does availability (that is, less downtime).
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Availability of a system may also be increased by the strategy of focusing on increasing testability and maintainability and not on reliability.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Improving maintainability is generally easier than improving reliability.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Maintainability estimates (repair rates) are also generally more accurate.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] However, because the uncertainties in the reliability estimates are in most cases very large, it is likely to dominate the availability (prediction uncertainty) problem, even while maintainability levels are very high.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Response time is the total amount of time it takes to respond to a request for service.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] In computing, that service can be any unit of work from a simple disk IO to loading a complex web page.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Most consumers pick a computer architecture (normally Intel IA-32 architecture) to be able to run a large base of pre-existing, pre-compiled software.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Being relatively uninformed on computer benchmarks, some of them pick a particular CPU based on operating frequency (see megahertz myth).
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Some system designers building parallel computers pick CPUs based on the speed per dollar.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Channel capacity is the tightest upper bound on the rate of information that can be reliably transmitted over a communications channel.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] By the noisy-channel coding theorem, the channel capacity of a given channel is the limiting information rate (in units of information per unit time) that can be achieved with arbitrarily small error probability.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Information theory, developed by Claude E.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Shannon during World War II, defines the notion of channel capacity and provides a mathematical model by which one can compute it.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] The key result states that the capacity of the channel, as defined above, is given by the maximum of the mutual information between the input and output of the channel, where the maximization is with respect to the input distribution.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Latency is a time delay between the cause and the effect of some physical change in the system being observed.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Latency is a result of the limited velocity with which any physical interaction can take place.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] This velocity is always lower than or equal to the speed of light.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Therefore, every physical system that has non-zero spatial dimensions will experience some sort of latency.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] The precise definition of latency depends on the system being observed and the nature of stimulation.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] In communications, the lower limit of latency is determined by the medium being used for communications.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] In reliable two-way communication systems, latency limits the maximum rate that information can be transmitted, as there is often a limit on the amount of information that is "in-flight" at any one moment.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] In the field of human-machine interaction, perceptible latency (delay between what the user commands and when the computer provides the results) has a strong effect on user satisfaction and usability.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Computers run sets of instructions called a process.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] In operating systems, the execution of the process can be postponed if other processes are also executing.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] In addition, the operating system can schedule when to perform the action that the process is commanding.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] For example, suppose a process commands that a computer card's voltage output be set high-low-high-low and so on at a rate of 1000 Hz.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] The operating system may choose to adjust the scheduling of each transition (high-low or low-high) based on an internal clock.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] The latency is the delay between the process instruction commanding the transition and the hardware actually transitioning the voltage from high to low or low to high.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] System designers building real-time computing systems want to guarantee worst-case response.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] That is easier to do when the CPU has low interrupt latency and when it has a deterministic response.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] In computer networking, bandwidth is a measurement of the bit rate of available or consumed data communication resources, expressed in bits per second or multiples of it (bit/s, kbit/s, Mbit/s, Gbit/s, etc.).
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Bandwidth sometimes defines the net bit rate (aka. peak bit rate, information rate, or physical layer useful bit rate), channel capacity, or the maximum throughput of a logical or physical communication path in a digital communication system.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] For example, bandwidth tests measure the maximum throughput of a computer network.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] The reason for this usage is that according to Hartley's law, the maximum data rate of a physical communication link is proportional to its bandwidth in hertz, which is sometimes called frequency bandwidth, spectral bandwidth, RF bandwidth, signal bandwidth or analog bandwidth.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] In general terms, throughput is the rate of production or the rate at which something can be processed.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] In communication networks, throughput is essentially synonymous with digital bandwidth consumption.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] In wireless networks or cellular communication networks, the system spectral efficiency in bit/s/Hz/area unit, bit/s/Hz/site or bit/s/Hz/cell, is the maximum system throughput (aggregate throughput) divided by the analog bandwidth and some measure of the system coverage area.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] In integrated circuits, often a block in a data flow diagram has a single input and a single output, and operates on discrete packets of information.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Examples of such blocks are FFT modules or binary multipliers.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Scalability is the ability of a system, network, or process to handle a growing amount of work in a capable manner or its ability to be enlarged to accommodate that growth.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] The amount of electric power used by the computer (power consumption).
[src:use-method/computer-performance] This becomes especially important for systems with limited power sources such as solar, batteries, and human power.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] System designers building parallel computers, such as Google's hardware, pick CPUs based on their speed per watt of power, because the cost of powering the CPU outweighs the cost of the CPU itself.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] For spaceflight computers, the processing speed per watt ratio is a more useful performance criterion than raw processing speed due to limited on-board resources of power.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Compression is useful because it helps reduce resource usage, such as data storage space or transmission capacity.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Because compressed data must be decompressed to be used, this extra processing imposes computational or other costs through decompression; this situation is far from being a free lunch.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Data compression is subject to a space–time complexity trade-off.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] This is a tradeoff involved in mobile systems, from the scale of smartphones to portable embedded systems in spacecraft.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] The effect of computing on the environment, during manufacturing and recycling as well as during use.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Measurements are taken with the objectives of reducing waste, reducing hazardous materials, and minimizing a computer's ecological footprint.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] The number of transistors on an integrated circuit (IC).
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Transistor count is the most common measure of IC complexity.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Because there are so many programs to test a CPU on all aspects of performance, benchmarks were developed.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] The most famous benchmarks are the SPECint and SPECfp benchmarks developed by Standard Performance Evaluation Corporation and the Certification Mark benchmark developed by the Embedded Microprocessor Benchmark Consortium EEMBC.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] In software engineering, performance testing is, in general, conducted to determine how a system performs in terms of responsiveness and stability under a particular workload.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] It can also serve to investigate, measure, validate, or verify other quality attributes of the system, such as scalability, reliability, and resource usage.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Performance testing is a subset of performance engineering, an emerging computer science practice which strives to build performance into the implementation, design, and architecture of a system.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] In software engineering, profiling ("program profiling", "software profiling") is a form of dynamic program analysis that measures, for example, the space (memory) or time complexity of a program, the usage of particular instructions, or frequency and duration of function calls.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] The most common use of profiling information is to aid program optimization.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Profiling is achieved by instrumenting either the program source code or its binary executable form using a tool called a *profiler* (or *code profiler*).
[src:use-method/computer-performance] A number of different techniques may be used by profilers, such as event-based, statistical, instrumented, and simulation methods.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] The central processing unit (CPU), also called the central processor, main processor, or simply the processor, is the primary processor in a given computer.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Its electronic circuits execute instructions of a computer program, such as arithmetic, logical, control, and input-output (I/O) operations.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] The performance or speed of a processor depends, among other things, on the clock frequency (usually measured in hertz) and the number of instructions per cycle (IPC), which together determine the number of instructions per second (IPS) the CPU can execute.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Many reported IPS values represent "peak" execution speeds for artificial instruction sequences with few branches, whereas real workloads consist of a mix of instructions and applications, some of which run longer than others.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] The performance of the memory hierarchy also greatly affects processor performance, a factor that is rarely considered when calculating IPS.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Due to these issues, various standardized tests, often called "benchmarks," such as SPECint, have been developed to attempt to measure real effective performance in commonly used applications.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Computer performance increases through the use of multicore processors, which essentially connect two or more separate processors (in this sense called cores) on a single integrated circuit.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Ideally, a dual-core processor should be almost twice as powerful as a single-core one.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] In practice, performance gains are much smaller, about 50%, due to imperfect software algorithms and implementation.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Increasing the number of cores in a processor (e.g., dual-core, quad-core, etc.) increases the workload it can handle.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] This means the processor can now process numerous asynchronous events, interrupts, and so forth, which might negatively impact the CPU under overload.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] These cores can be viewed as different floors in a processing plant, where each floor handles its own task.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Sometimes these cores will process the same tasks as neighboring cores if one core is insufficient for handling the information.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Multicore CPUs enhance a computer's ability to perform multiple tasks simultaneously by providing additional computational power.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] However, the speed increase is not directly proportional to the number of cores added.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] This is because cores need to interact via specific channels, and this inter-core communication consumes part of the available computing power.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Due to the specific capabilities of modern CPUs, such as simultaneous multithreading and uncore— which imply shared use of actual CPU resources to improve utilization—monitoring performance levels and hardware usage has gradually become a more complex task.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] In response, some CPUs implement additional hardware logic that tracks the actual utilization of various parts of the CPU and provides various counters accessible to software; an example is Intel's Performance Counter Monitor technology.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Performance tuning is the improvement of system performance.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] This is typically a computer application, but the same methods can be applied to economic markets, bureaucracies or other complex systems.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] The motivation for such activity is called a performance problem, which can be real or anticipated.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Most systems will respond to increased load with some degree of decreasing performance.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] A system's ability to accept a higher load is called scalability, and modifying a system to handle a higher load is synonymous with performance tuning.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Measure the performance of the system before modification.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Identify the part of the system that is critical for improving the performance.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Modify that part of the system to remove the bottleneck.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Measure the performance of the system after modification.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] If the modification makes the performance better, adopt it.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] If the modification makes the performance worse, put it back to the way it was.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Perceived performance, in computer engineering, refers to how quickly a software feature appears to perform its task.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] The concept applies mainly to user acceptance aspects.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] The amount of time an application takes to start up, or a file to download, is not made faster by showing a startup screen (see Splash screen) or a file progress dialog box.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] However, it satisfies some human needs: it appears faster to the user and also provides a visual cue to let them know the system is handling their request.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] In most cases, increasing real performance increases perceived performance, but when real performance cannot be increased due to physical limitations, techniques can be used to increase perceived performance.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] A CPU designer is often required to implement a particular instruction set, and so cannot change N.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] Sometimes a designer focuses on improving performance by making significant improvements in f (with techniques such as deeper pipelines and faster caches), while (hopefully) not sacrificing too much C—leading to a speed-demon CPU design.
[src:use-method/computer-performance] For a given instruction set (and therefore fixed N) and semiconductor process, the maximum single-thread performance (1/t) requires a balance between brainiac techniques and speedracer techniques.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] Measuring CPU time for two functionally identical programs that process identical inputs can indicate which program is faster, but it is a common misunderstanding that CPU time can be used to compare *algorithms*.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] Comparing programs by their CPU time compares specific *implementations* of algorithms.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] (It is possible to have both efficient and inefficient implementations of the same algorithm.) Algorithms are more commonly compared using measures of time complexity and space complexity.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] Typically, the CPU time used by a program is measured by the operating system, which schedules all of the work of the CPU.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] Modern multitasking operating systems run hundreds of processes.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] (A process is a running program.) Upon starting a process, the operating system records the time using an internal timer.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] When the process is suspended or terminated, the operating system again records the time.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] The total time that a process spent running is its CPU time, as shown in the figure.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] The process "accounting" done by the Unix family of operating systems includes two components of **CPU time**.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] User time and System time reflect the fact that most programs make requests to the operating system while they execute.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] Input/output operations, such as reading a file or writing to the screen, are done by issuing requests to the operating system, possibly through system calls.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] I/O and other operations performed by the operating system on behalf of a process constitute system time.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] Other operating systems such as Microsoft Windows similarly has separate accounting for "kernel time", which is a very similar concept as "system time".
[src:use-method/cpu-time] In contrast, elapsed real time (or simply real time, or wall-clock time) is the time taken from the start of a computer program until the end as measured by an ordinary clock.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] Elapsed real time includes User time, System time, plus time that the process was not running for any reason, such as when its execution was preempted.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] The Unix command top provides CPU time, priority, elapsed real time, and other information for all processes and updates it in real time.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] The Unix command time prints CPU time and elapsed real time for the execution of a Unix command (or pipeline).
[src:use-method/cpu-time] Note that many command-line shells have their own implementation of this command.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] This process took a total of 0.02 seconds of CPU time (User + System).
[src:use-method/cpu-time] The reported System time is 0.00 seconds, indicating that the amount of System time used was less than the printed resolution of 0.01 seconds.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] The following is the source code of the application nextPrimeNumber which was used in the above example.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] Modern CPUs have several clocks and counters, such as the Time Stamp Counter, the High Precision Event Timer, and the Real-time Clock, each with a specialized use.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] When a program wants to time its own operation, it can use a function like the POSIX **`clock()`** function, which returns the **CPU time** used by the program.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] POSIX allows this clock to start at an arbitrary value, so to measure elapsed time, a program calls **`clock()`**, does some work, then calls **`clock()`** again.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] The difference is the time needed to do the work.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] The POSIX function **`getrusage()`** returns more than just the CPU time consumed by a process in a POSIX environment.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] It returns many measurements of a process, often including approximate memory usage and Context switch (scheduling) event counts.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] Functionality varies across operating systems.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] On multi-processor and multi-core machines, a program can use two or more processors simultaneously in what is called parallel processing.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] In such situations, a measure of *total CPU time* is useful, which is the sum of CPU time consumed by all of the processors utilized by the program.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] In computing, **elapsed real time**, **real time**, **wall-clock time**, **wall time**, or **walltime** is the actual time taken from the start of a computer program to the end.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] In other words, it is the difference between the time at which a task finishes and the time at which the task started.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] Wall time is thus different from CPU time, which measures only the time during which the processor is actively working on a certain task or process.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] The difference between the two can arise from architecture and run-time dependent factors, e.g. programmed delays or waiting for system resources to become available.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] Elapsed real time is always greater than or equal to the CPU time for computer programs which use only one CPU for processing.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] If no waiting occurs, such as for I/O, and the program's execution is never preempted, elapsed real time and CPU time will be virtually identical.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] If a program uses parallel processing, total CPU time for that program is typically more than its elapsed real time.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] For a program that is able to evenly divide its work across two processors with no overhead in doing so, the value (Total CPU time)/(Number of processors) will be virtually identical to elapsed real time.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] Here, a *processor* may be a (single-core) CPU or one core in a multi-core CPU.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] Example: A software application executed on a four-core processor creates four Unix processes.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] If each process is able to execute on a separate processor core, computation proceeds on four processor cores simultaneously.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] The total CPU time would be, ideally, four times the elapsed real time.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] In reality, parallel processing rarely achieves a linear speedup, where the amount of computation per unit time scales up with the number of processors in use.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] Some embarrassingly parallel problems admit such solutions, but for most, additional work is required to divide up the computation when the program starts, and to combine the results from each processor at the end.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] The additional work adds to the total CPU time.
[src:use-method/cpu-time] Frequently, a process finds itself waiting for data from another process before it can continue, which also adds to the total time.
[src:use-method/load-computing] In UNIX computing, the system **load** is a measure of the amount of computational work that a computer system performs.
[src:use-method/load-computing] The **load average** represents the average system load over a period of time.
[src:use-method/load-computing] It conventionally appears in the form of three numbers which represent the system load during the last one-, five-, and fifteen-minute periods.
[src:use-method/load-computing] The Unix *load number* refers to the number of processes using or waiting for CPU; i.e., the number of processes in the *ready queue* or run queue.
[src:use-method/load-computing] An idle computer has a load number of 0 (the idle process is not counted).
[src:use-method/load-computing] Each running process increments the load number by 1.
[src:use-method/load-computing] Each process that terminates decrements it by 1.
[src:use-method/load-computing] Most UNIX systems count only processes in the *running* (on CPU) or *runnable* (waiting for CPU) states (state R).
[src:use-method/load-computing] In addition to processes in "R" state, Linux also includes processes in uninterruptible sleep states (usually waiting for disk activity; state "D"), which can lead to markedly different results if many processes remain blocked in I/O due to a busy or stalled I/O system.
[src:use-method/load-computing] This, for example, includes processes blocking due to an NFS server failure or too slow media (e.g., USB 1.x storage devices).
[src:use-method/load-computing] Such circumstances can result in an elevated load average, which does not reflect an actual increase in CPU use.
[src:use-method/load-computing] The idea behind its inclusion is that while disk wait is not the same as CPU-wait, it still reflects how long a user needs to wait.
[src:use-method/load-computing] On modern UNIX systems, the treatment of threading with respect to load averages varies.
[src:use-method/load-computing] Some systems treat threads as processes for the purposes of load average calculation: each thread waiting to run will add 1 to the load.
[src:use-method/load-computing] Linux appears to count each thread separately as adding 1 to the load.
[src:use-method/load-computing] If desired, one can also add uninterruptible "disk" wait state, labelled "D" on Linux and FreeBSD, "U" on macOS.
[src:use-method/load-computing] `-M` may be used to get per-thread information on Linux and macOS, but not FreeBSD, where the option is instead `-H`.
[src:use-method/load-computing] (The load reported will never be 0, as the `ps` process itself is counted.
[src:use-method/load-computing] On Linux specifically, the procfs file `/proc/stat` contains two lines `procs_running` and `procs_blocked`, corresponding to scheduling entities (processes/threads) in "R" and "D" states respectively.
[src:use-method/load-computing] This can be used to read the current load instead of `ps`.
[src:use-method/load-computing] As with before, the load reported includes the program currently reading the procfs file, so subtract one from the sum to obtain the true load.
[src:use-method/load-computing] The comparative study of different load indices carried out by Ferrari et al. reported that CPU load information based upon the CPU queue length does much better in load balancing compared to CPU utilization.
[src:use-method/load-computing] The reason CPU queue length did better is probably because when a host is heavily loaded, its CPU utilization is likely to be close to 100%, and it is unable to reflect the exact load level of the utilization.
[src:use-method/load-computing] In contrast, CPU queue lengths can directly reflect the amount of load on a CPU.
[src:use-method/load-computing] As an example, two systems, one with 3 and the other with 6 processes in the queue, are both very likely to have utilizations close to 100%, although they would obviously differ in terms of process wait-times.
[src:use-method/load-computing] All Unix and Unix-like systems generate a dimensionless metric of three "load average" numbers in the kernel.
[src:use-method/load-computing] The `w` and `top` commands show the same three load average numbers, as do a range of graphical user interface utilities.
[src:use-method/load-computing] The underlying interface is `getloadavg()`, a C function present on most UNIX systems since 4.3BSD-Reno of 1990 (but is not part of POSIX).
[src:use-method/load-computing] On Linux specifically, one can also read `/proc/loadavg` for this information.
[src:use-method/load-computing] This file also provides instantaneous information on the number of processes in "R" state, the total number of processes, and the process ID of the most-recently-created process.
[src:use-method/load-computing] Systems calculate the load *average* as the exponentially damped/weighted moving average of the load *number*.
[src:use-method/load-computing] The three values of load average refer to the past one, five, and fifteen minutes of system operation.
[src:use-method/load-computing] Mathematically speaking, all three values always average all the system load since the system started up.
[src:use-method/load-computing] They all decay exponentially, but they decay at different *speeds*: they decay exponentially by *e* after 1, 5, and 15 minutes respectively.
[src:use-method/load-computing] Hence, the 1-minute load average consists of 63% (more precisely: 1 - 1/*e*) of the load from the last minute and 37% (1/*e*) of the average load since start up, excluding the last minute.
[src:use-method/load-computing] For the 5- and 15-minute load averages, the same 63%/37% ratio is computed over 5 minutes and 15 minutes, respectively.
[src:use-method/load-computing] Therefore, it is not technically accurate that the 1-minute load average only includes the last 60 seconds of activity, as it includes 37% of the activity from the past, but it is correct to state that it includes *mostly* the last minute.
[src:use-method/load-computing] For single-CPU systems that are CPU bound, one can think of load average as a measure of system utilization during the respective time period.
[src:use-method/load-computing] For systems with multiple CPUs, one must divide the load by the number of processors in order to get a comparable measure.
[src:use-method/load-computing] This implies that this system could have handled all the work scheduled for the last minute if it were 1.73 times as fast.
[src:use-method/load-computing] In a system with four CPUs, a load average of 3.73 would indicate that there were, on average, 3.73 processes ready to run.
[src:use-method/load-computing] Because this is fewer than 4, we know each one could be scheduled into a CPU, and that no overloading is present.
[src:use-method/load-computing] On Linux systems, the load-average is not calculated on each clock tick, but driven by a variable value that is based on the `HZ` frequency setting and tested on each clock tick.
[src:use-method/load-computing] This setting defines the kernel clock tick rate in hertz (times per second), and it defaults to 100 for 10 ms ticks.
[src:use-method/load-computing] Kernel activities use this number of ticks to time themselves.
[src:use-method/load-computing] Specifically, the `calc_load()` function (in loadavg.h, formerly sched.h), which calculates the load average, nominally runs every `LOAD_FREQ (5*HZ+1)` ticks, i.e. a tiny bit over 5 s.
[src:use-method/load-computing] The avenrun array contains 1-minute, 5-minute and 15-minute average.
[src:use-method/load-computing] The `calc_load()` function provides the correct update of the load-average for the default update rate of `LOAD_FREQ (5*HZ+1)`.
[src:use-method/load-computing] NO_HZ is a mode meant to reduce the number of scheduling-clock interrupts on idle processors, which improves power efficiency and reduces clock jitter.
[src:use-method/load-computing] This would cause processors to miss their update ticks, however.
[src:use-method/load-computing] As a result, the counting of tasks is done using atomic operations.
[src:use-method/load-computing] Here `fixed_power_int` (not included in article) raises exp to its nth power in fixed-point arithmetic.
[src:use-method/load-computing] The "sampled" calculation of load averages is a somewhat common behavior; FreeBSD, too, only refreshes the value every five seconds.
[src:use-method/load-computing] The interval is usually taken to not be exact so that they do not collect processes that are scheduled to fire at a certain moment.
[src:use-method/load-computing] This is the reason for "+1" in the Linux code from above; FreeBSD instead uses a pseudorandom offset added to the interval.
[src:use-method/load-computing] `loadavg.h` also mentions that the use of 11 fractional bits in the above fixed point calculation prevents reducing the interval (`LOAD_FREQ`) much lower.
[src:use-method/load-computing] For example, a two-second interval would result in the EXP values becoming 1981, 2034 and 2043, nearly saturating the precision available (0–2047).
[src:use-method/load-computing] Ripke Klaus has shown in 2011 that the "+1" modification alone is not sufficient to avoid Moiré artifacts from regularly-scheduled processes.
[src:use-method/load-computing] His experiments suggest 4.61 to be a better value: 0.61 is close to the golden ratio, which helps spread out the sample-point among fractional seconds.
[src:use-method/load-computing] At the same time, 4.61 is close to 60⁄13, so the property of 5 s being an integer fraction of 60 s is maintained.
[src:use-method/load-computing] Ripke's change is common among Android system kernels, although the exact expression used (`4*HZ+61`) assumes an HZ of 100.
[src:use-method/load-computing] `60*HZ/13` would be more appropriate for varying values of HZ.
[src:use-method/load-computing] As we've discussed before, most kernels use fixed-point arithmetic to calculate the load average for efficiency and simplicity.
[src:use-method/load-computing] This however limits the achievable update-rate and precision.
[src:use-method/load-computing] Given that we have established how to get the instantaneous load from userspace, it is also possible to calculate the load average from userspace.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] As the connection between application success and business success continues to gain recognition, particularly in the mobile space, application performance engineering has taken on a preventive and perfective role within the software development life cycle.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] As such, the term is typically used to describe the processes, people and technologies required to effectively test non-functional requirements, ensure adherence to service levels and optimize application performance prior to deployment.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] The term *performance engineering* encompasses more than just the software and supporting infrastructure, and as such the term performance engineering is preferable from a macro view.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] Adherence to the non-functional requirements is also validated post-deployment by monitoring the production systems.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] This is part of IT service management (see also ITIL).
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] Performance engineering has become a separate discipline at a number of large corporations, with tasking separate but parallel to systems engineering.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] It is pervasive, involving people from multiple organizational units; but predominantly within the information technology organization.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] Because this discipline is applied within multiple methodologies, the following activities will occur within differently specified phases.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] During the first, Conceptual phase of a program or project, critical business processes are identified.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] Typically they are classified as critical based upon revenue value, cost savings, or other assigned business value.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] This classification is done by the business unit, not the IT organization.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] High level risks that may impact system performance are identified and described at this time.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] An example might be known performance risks for a particular vendor system.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] Finally, performance activities, roles and deliverables are identified for the Elaboration phase.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] Activities and resource loading are incorporated into the Elaboration phase project plans.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] During this defining phase, the critical business processes are decomposed to critical use cases.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] Probe cases will be decomposed further, as needed, to single page (screen) transitions.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] These are the use cases that will be subjected to script driven performance testing.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] The type of requirements that relate to performance engineering are the non-functional requirements, or NFR.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] While a functional requirement relates to which business operations are to be performed, a performance related non-functional requirement will relate to how fast that business operation performs under defined circumstances.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] Early in this phase a number of performance tool related activities are required.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] The performance test team normally does not execute performance tests in the development environment, but rather in a specialized pre-deployment environment that is configured to be as close as possible to the planned production environment.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] This team will execute performance testing against test cases, validating that the critical use cases conform to the specified non-functional requirements.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] The team will execute load testing against a normally expected (median) load as well as a peak load.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] They will often run stress tests that will identify the system bottlenecks.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] The data gathered, and the analysis, will be fed back to the group that does performance tuning.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] Where necessary, the system will be tuned to bring nonconforming tests into conformance with the non-functional requirements.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] If performance engineering has been properly applied at each iteration and phase of the project to this point, hopefully this will be sufficient to enable the system to receive performance certification.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] However, if for some reason (perhaps proper performance engineering working practices were not applied) there are tests that cannot be tuned into compliance, then it will be necessary to return portions of the system to development for refactoring.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] In some cases the problem can be resolved with additional hardware, but adding more hardware leads quickly to diminishing returns.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] During this final phase the system is deployed to the production environment.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] A number of preparatory steps are required.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] In the operational domain (post production deployment) performance engineering focuses primarily within three areas: service level management, capacity management, and problem management.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] In the service level management area, performance engineering is concerned with service level agreements and the associated systems monitoring that serves to validate service level compliance, detect problems, and identify trends.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] For example, when real user monitoring is deployed it is possible to ensure that user transactions are being executed in conformance with specified non-functional requirements.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] Transaction response time is logged in a database such that queries and reports can be run against the data.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] This permits trend analysis that can be useful for capacity management.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] When user transactions fall out of band, the events should generate alerts so that attention may be applied to the situation.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] For capacity management, performance engineering focuses on ensuring that the systems will remain within performance compliance.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] This means executing trend analysis on historical monitoring generated data, such that the future time of non compliance is predictable.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] For example, if a system is showing a trend of slowing transaction processing (which might be due to growing data set sizes, or increasing numbers of concurrent users, or other factors) then at some point the system will no longer meet the criteria specified within the service level agreements.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] Capacity management is charged with ensuring that additional capacity is added in advance of that point (additional CPUs, more memory, new database indexing, et cetera) so that the trend lines are reset and the system will remain within the specified performance range.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] Within the problem management domain, the performance engineering practices are focused on resolving the root cause of performance related problems.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] These typically involve system tuning, changing operating system or device parameters, or even refactoring the application software to resolve poor performance due to poor design or bad coding practices.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] To ensure that there is proper feedback validating that the system meets the NFR specified performance metrics, any major system needs a monitoring subsystem.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] The planning, design, installation, configuration, and control of the monitoring subsystem are specified by an appropriately defined monitoring process.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] The trend analysis component of this cannot be undervalued.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] This functionality, properly implemented, will enable predicting when a given application undergoing gradually increasing user loads and growing data sets will exceed the specified non functional performance requirements for a given use case.
[src:use-method/performance-engineering] This permits proper management budgeting, acquisition of, and deployment of the required resources to keep the system running within the parameters of the non functional performance requirements.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] A computer **system resource** is any hardware or software aspect of limited availability that is accessible to a computer system.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] Like any resource, computer system resources can be exhausted, and issues arise due to scarcity.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] Resource management, a key aspect of designing hardware and software, includes preventing resource leaks (not releasing a resource done with it) and handling resource contention (when multiple processes want to access the same resource).
[src:use-method/resource-computing] Computing resources are used in cloud computing to provide services through networks.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] A linearly addressable resource, such as memory and storage, can be used for an allocation that is either *contiguous* or *non-contiguous*.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] For example, dynamic memory is generally allocated as a contiguous block that consists of a portion of memory from a starting address and running for a certain length.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] On the other hand, storage space is typically allocated by a file system as non-contiguous blocks throughout the storage device even though consumers of a file can treat it as a linear sequence; logically contiguous.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] The resource has an overall capacity as well as the capacity to support an allocation of a certain size.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] For example, RAM might have enough free space to support allocating 1024 1MB blocks although not enough contiguous free space to support allocating a single 1GB block even though the sum of the smaller blocks equals the size of the large block.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] Fragmentation describes the amount to which linear resources are stored non-contiguously, and a highly fragmented resource may degrade performance.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] One can also distinguish *compressible* from *incompressible* resources.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] Compressible resources, such as CPU and network bandwidth, can be throttled benignly.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] The user will be slowed proportionally to the throttling, but will otherwise proceed normally.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] Other resources, such as memory, cannot be throttled without either causing failure (inability to allocate memory typically causes failure) or performance degradation, such as due to thrashing (paging slows processing throughput).
[src:use-method/resource-computing] For example, a paging system can allow main memory (primary storage) to be compressed (by paging to secondary storage), and some systems allow discardable memory for caches, which is compressible without disastrous performance impact.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] Without sufficient power an electrical device cannot run, and will stop or crash.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] But, some devices, such as mobile phones, support degraded operation at reduced power.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] Some devices allow for suspending operations (without loss of data) until power is restored.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] The types of resources and issues that arise due to their scarcity is vast.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] For example, memory is a resource since a computer has a fixed amount.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] For many applications, the amount is so large compared to its needs that the resource is essentially unlimited.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] But, if many application with modest requirements are running concurrently, or if an application does require large amounts of memory, then runtime issues occur as the amount of free memory approaches zero.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] Applications are no longer able to allocate memory and will probably fail.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] Another well-known resource is the processor.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] It differs from memory in that it is not reserved.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] Nonetheless, as the processor becomes more loaded with work, the time waiting for the processor increases, and processing throughput degrades.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] This often leads to inferior user experience or in a time-critical application, loss of critical system functionality.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] Resources can be layered and intertwined.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] For example, a file is a resource since each file is unique.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] A file consumes storage space which has a fixed size.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] When a file is opened, generally memory is allocated for the purpose of accessing the file.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] This file object is both a unique resource and consumes memory (a resource).
[src:use-method/resource-computing] Some resources are accessed via a handle such as a lookup table key or pointer.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] Although the handle may consume memory, the handle itself is not considered a resource since it can be duplicated at little cost.
[src:use-method/resource-computing] On the boot process of the modern operating systems, the ACPI protocol or the Devicetree protocol is often used to deliver hardware resources information.
[src:use-method/usemethod] The Utilization Saturation and Errors (USE) Method is a methodology for analyzing the performance of any system.
[src:use-method/usemethod] It directs the construction of a checklist, which for server analysis can be used for quickly identifying resource bottlenecks or errors.
[src:use-method/usemethod] It begins by posing questions, and then seeks answers, instead of beginning with given metrics (partial answers) and trying to work backwards.
[src:use-method/usemethod] The resulting USE Method-derived checklists for different operating systems are listed on the left navigation panel (Linux, Solaris, etc).
[src:use-method/usemethod] You can customize these for your environment, adding additional tools that your site uses.
[src:use-method/usemethod] There is also the Rosetta Stone of Performance Checklists, automatically generated from some of these.
[src:use-method/usemethod] Performance monitoring products can make the USE method easier to follow by providing its metrics via an easy-to-use interface.
[src:use-method/usemethod] A serious performance issue arises, and you suspect it's caused by the server.
[src:use-method/usemethod] Getting started can be the hardest part.
[src:use-method/usemethod] I developed the USE Method to teach others how to solve common performance issues quickly, without overlooking important areas.
[src:use-method/usemethod] Like an emergency checklist in a flight manual, it is intended to be simple, straightforward, complete, and fast.
[src:use-method/usemethod] The USE Method has been used successfully countless times in different enterprise environments, classroom environments (as a learning tool), and more recently in cloud computing environments.
[src:use-method/usemethod] The USE Method is based on three metric types and a strategy for approaching a complex system.
[src:use-method/usemethod] I find it solves about 80% of server issues with 5% of the effort, and, as I will demonstrate, it can be applied to systems other than servers.
[src:use-method/usemethod] It should be thought of as a tool, one that is part of larger toolbox of methodologies.
[src:use-method/usemethod] There are many problem types it doesn't solve, which will require other methods and longer time spans.
[src:use-method/usemethod] It's intended to be used early in a performance investigation, to identify systemic bottlenecks.
[src:use-method/usemethod] Errors should be investigated because they can degrade performance, and may not be immediately noticed when the failure mode is recoverable.
[src:use-method/usemethod] This includes operations that fail and are retried, and devices from a pool of redundant devices that fail.
[src:use-method/usemethod] A burst of high utilization can cause saturation and performance issues, even though utilization is *low* when averaged over a long interval.
[src:use-method/usemethod] I had an example where a customer had problems with CPU saturation (latency) even though their monitoring tools showed CPU utilization was never higher than 80%.
[src:use-method/usemethod] The monitoring tool was reporting five minute averages, during which CPU utilization hit 100% for seconds at a time.
[src:use-method/usemethod] To begin with, you need a list of resources to iterate through.
[src:use-method/usemethod] Some components are two types of resources: storage devices are a service request resource (I/O) and also a capacity resource (population).
[src:use-method/usemethod] Both types can become a system bottleneck.
[src:use-method/usemethod] Request resources can be defined as *queueing systems*, which can queue and then service requests.
[src:use-method/usemethod] Some physical components have been left out, such as hardware caches (eg, MMU TLB/TSB, CPU).
[src:use-method/usemethod] The USE Method is most effective for resources that suffer performance degradation under high utilization or saturation, leading to a bottleneck.
[src:use-method/usemethod] Caches *improve* performance under high utilization.
[src:use-method/usemethod] Cache hit rates and other performance attributes can be checked after the USE Method - after systemic bottlenecks have been ruled out.
[src:use-method/usemethod] If you are unsure whether to include a resource, include it, then see how well the metrics work.
[src:use-method/usemethod] Another way to iterate over resources is to find or draw a Functional Block Diagram for the system.
[src:use-method/usemethod] These also show relationships, which can be very useful when looking for bottlenecks in the flow of data.
[src:use-method/usemethod] I love these diagrams, although they can be hard to come by.
[src:use-method/usemethod] Hardware engineers can be the best resource – the people who actually build the things.
[src:use-method/usemethod] While determining utilization for the various busses, annotate each bus on the functional diagram with its maximum bandwidth.
[src:use-method/usemethod] This results in a diagram where systemic bottlenecks may be identified before a single measurement has been taken.
[src:use-method/usemethod] CPU, memory and I/O interconnects are often overlooked.
[src:use-method/usemethod] Fortunately, they aren't commonly the system bottleneck.
[src:use-method/usemethod] Unfortunately, if they are, it can be difficult to do much about (maybe you can upgrade the main board, or reduce load: eg, "zero copy" projects lighten memory bus load).
[src:use-method/usemethod] With the USE Method, at least you become aware of what you weren't considering: interconnect performance.
[src:use-method/usemethod] See Analyzing the HyperTransport for an example of an interconnect issue which I identified with the USE Method.
[src:use-method/usemethod] Given the list of resources, consider the metric types: utilization, saturation and errors.
[src:use-method/usemethod] In the table below, think about each resource and metric type, and see if you can fill in the blanks.
[src:use-method/usemethod] I've left off timing: these metrics are either averages per interval or counts.
[src:use-method/usemethod] I've also left off how to fetch them: for your custom checklist, include which OS tool or monitoring software to use, and which statistic to read.
[src:use-method/usemethod] For those metrics that aren't available, write "?".
[src:use-method/usemethod] You will end up with a checklist that is easy and quick to follow, and is as complete as possible for your system.
[src:use-method/usemethod] These typically get harder to measure, depending on the OS, and I often have to write my own software to do them (eg, the "amd64htcpu" script from Analyzing the HyperTransport).
[src:use-method/usemethod] Repeat for all combinations, and include instructions for fetching each metric.
[src:use-method/usemethod] You'll end up with a list of about thirty metrics, some of which can't be measured, and some of which are tricky to measure.
[src:use-method/usemethod] Fortunately, the most common issues are usually found with the easy ones (eg, CPU saturation, memory capacity saturation, network interface utilization, disk utilization), which can be checked first.
[src:use-method/usemethod] See the top of this page for the example checklists for Linux, Solaris, Mac OS X, FreeBSD, etc.
[src:use-method/usemethod] Reading metrics for every combination on your OS can very time consuming, especially once you start working through bus and interconnect metrics.
[src:use-method/usemethod] You may only have time to check a subset: CPUs, memory capacity, storage capacity, storage device I/O, network interfaces.
[src:use-method/usemethod] The USE Method has made you aware of what you didn't check: what were once unknown-unknowns are now known-unknowns.
[src:use-method/usemethod] And for that time when it's vital for your company to root cause a performance issue, you already have a to-do list of known extra work that can be performed for more thorough analysis, completing the USE Method for when it's really needed.
[src:use-method/usemethod] It's hoped that the subset of metrics that are easy to check grows over time, as more metrics are added to OSes to make the USE Method easier.
[src:use-method/usemethod] Performance monitoring software can also help, adding USE method wizards to do the work for you.
[src:use-method/usemethod] Some software resources can be considered in a similar way.
[src:use-method/usemethod] This usually applies to smaller components of software, not entire applications.
[src:use-method/usemethod] If the metrics work well, use them, otherwise software can be left to other methodologies (eg, latency).
[src:use-method/usemethod] The USE Method helps you identify which metrics to use.
[src:use-method/usemethod] After learning how to read them from the operating system, your next task is to interpret their current values.
[src:use-method/usemethod] For some, interpretation may be obvious (and well documented).
[src:use-method/usemethod] Others, not so obvious, and may depend on workload requirements or expectations.
[src:use-method/usemethod] It's easy to interpret the negative case: low utilization, no saturation, no errors.
[src:use-method/usemethod] This is more useful than it sounds - narrowing down the scope of an investigation can quickly bring focus to the problem area.
[src:use-method/usemethod] In a cloud computing environment, software resource controls may be in place to limit or throttle tenants who are sharing one system.
[src:use-method/usemethod] This can include hypervisor or container (cgroup) limits for memory, CPU, network, and storage I/O.
[src:use-method/usemethod] External hardware may also impose limits, such as for network throughput.
[src:use-method/usemethod] Each of these resource limits can be examined with the USE Method, similar to examining the physical resources.
[src:use-method/usemethod] For example, in our environment "memory capacity utilization" can be the tenant's memory usage vs its memory cap.
[src:use-method/usemethod] "memory capacity saturation" can be seen by anonymous paging activity, even though the traditional Unix page scanner may be idle.
[src:use-method/usemethod] The USE Method is pictured as a flowchart below.
[src:use-method/usemethod] Note that errors can be checked before utilization and saturation, as a minor optimization (they are usually quicker and easier to interpret).
[src:use-method/usemethod] The USE Method identifies problems which are likely to be system bottlenecks.
[src:use-method/usemethod] Unfortunately, systems can be suffering more than one performance problem, and so the first one you find may be *a* problem but not *the* problem.
[src:use-method/usemethod] Each discovery can be investigated using further methodologies, before continuing the USE Method as needed to iterate over more resources.
[src:use-method/usemethod] Strategies for further analysis include workload characterization and drill-down analysis.
[src:use-method/usemethod] After completing these (if needed), you should have evidence for whether the corrective action is to adjust the load applied or to tune the resource itself.
[src:use-method/usemethod] I said earlier that the USE Method could be applied beyond servers.
[src:use-method/usemethod] Looking for a fun example, I thought of a system in which I have no expertise at all, and no idea where to start: the Apollo Lunar Module guidance system.
[src:use-method/usemethod] The USE Method provides a simple procedure to try.
[src:use-method/usemethod] The first step is to find a list of resources, or better still, a functional block diagram.
[src:use-method/usemethod] Some of these components may not exhibit utilization or saturation characteristics.
[src:use-method/usemethod] After iterating through them, this can be redrawn to only include relevant components.
[src:use-method/usemethod] I'll start with the Apollo guidance computer (AGC) itself.
[src:use-method/usemethod] Some of these details may be familiar to space ethusiasts: 1201 ("NO VAC AREAS") and 1202 alarms famously occurred during the Apollo 11 descent.
[src:use-method/usemethod] ("VAC" is short for "vector accumulator", extra storage for jobs that process vector quantities; I think wikipedia's description as "vacant" may be incorrect).
[src:use-method/usemethod] Given Apollo 11's 1201 alarm, analysis can continue using other methodologies, such as workload characterization.
[src:use-method/usemethod] The workload is mostly applied via interrupts, many of which can be seen in the functional diagram.
[src:use-method/usemethod] This includes the rendezvous radar, used to track the Command Module, which was interrupting the AGC with work even though the LM was performing descent.
[src:use-method/usemethod] This is an example of finding unnecessary work (or low priority work; some updates from the radar may have been desirable so that the LM AGC could immediately calculate an abort trajectory and CM rendezvous if needed).
[src:use-method/usemethod] As a harder example, I'll examine the rendezvous radar as a resource.
[src:use-method/usemethod] There are three types: "DATA NO GOOD", "NO TRACK", and "SHAFT- AND TRUNNION-AXIS ERROR" signals.
[src:use-method/usemethod] Utilization is harder: one type may be utilization of the drive motors - defined as the time they were busy responding to angle commands (seen in the functional diagram via the "COUPLING DATA UNIT").
[src:use-method/usemethod] I'll need to read the LM docs more to see if there saturation characteristics either with the drive motors or with the returned radar data.
[src:use-method/usemethod] In a short amount of time, using this methodology, I've gone from having no idea where to start, to having specific metrics to look for and research.
[src:use-method/usemethod] While the USE Method may find 80% of server issues, latency-based methodologies (eg, Method R) can approach finding 100% of all issues.
[src:use-method/usemethod] However, these can take much more time if you are unfamiliar with software internals.
[src:use-method/usemethod] They may be more suited for database administrators or application developers, who already have this familiarity.
[src:use-method/usemethod] The USE Method is more suited for junior or senior system administrators, whose responsibility and expertise includes the operating system (OS) and hardware.
[src:use-method/usemethod] It can also be employed by these other staff when a quick check of system health is desired.
[src:use-method/usemethod] For each tool, list useful metrics it provides.
[src:use-method/usemethod] For each metric, list possible interpretation rules.
[src:use-method/usemethod] The result of this is a prescriptive checklist showing which tool to run, which metrics to read, and how to interpret them.
[src:use-method/usemethod] While this can be fairly effective, one problem is that it relies exclusively on available (or known) tools, which can provide an incomplete view of the system.
[src:use-method/usemethod] The user is also unaware that they have an incomplete view - and so the problem will remain.
[src:use-method/usemethod] The USE Method, instead, iterates over the system resources to create a complete list of questions to ask, then searches for tools to answer them.
[src:use-method/usemethod] A more complete view is constructed, and unknown areas are documented and their existence known ("known unknowns").
[src:use-method/usemethod] Based on USE, a similar checklist can be developed showing which tool to run (where available), which metric to read, and how to interpret it.
[src:use-method/usemethod] Another problem can be when iterating through a large number of tools distracts from the goal - to find bottlenecks.
[src:use-method/usemethod] The USE Method provides a strategy to find bottlenecks and errors efficiently, even with an unwieldy number of available tools and metrics.
[src:use-method/usemethod] The USE Method is a simple strategy you can use to perform a complete a check of system health, identifying common bottlenecks and errors.
[src:use-method/usemethod] It can be deployed early in the investigation and quickly identify problem areas, which then can be studied in more detail other methodologies, if need be.
[src:use-method/usemethod] The strength of USE is its speed and visibility: by considering all resources, you are unlikely to overlook any issues.
[src:use-method/usemethod] It will, however, only find certain types of issues – bottlenecks and errors – and should be considered as one tool in a larger toolbox.
[src:use-method/usemethod] I explained the USE Method on this page and provided generic examples of metrics.
[src:use-method/usemethod] See the example checklists in the left navigation pane for specific operating systems, where tools and metrics to apply the USE Method are suggested.
[src:use-method/usemethod] Also see the complementary thread-based methodology, the TSA Method.
